st:2: fundamental declaraions
st:2: _of the_
st:2: province
tb: As the Anglican Church in North America (the Province),
    being a part of the One, Holy, Catholic, and Apostolic Church
    of Christ, we believe and confess Jesus Christ to be the Way, the
    Truth, and the Life: no one comes to the Father but by Him.
    Therefore, we identify the following seven elements as charac-
    teristic of the Anglican Way, and essential for membership:
ol:1: We confess the canonical books of the Old and New
    Testaments to be the inspired Word of God, containing all
    things necessary for salvation, and to be the final authority
    and unchangeable standard for Christian faith and life.
ol:2: We confess Baptism and the Supper of the Lord to be
    Sacraments ordained by Christ Himself in the Gospel, and
    thus to be ministered with unfailing use of His words of
    institution and of the elements ordained by Him.
ol:3: We confess the godly historic Episcopate as an inherent part
    the fullness and unity of the Body of Christ.
    of the apostolic faith and practice, and therefore as integral to

pb:767
ol:4: We confess as proved by most certain warrants of Holy
    Scripture the historic faith of the undivided church as
    declared in the three Catholic Creeds: the Apostles’, the
    Nicene, and the Athanasian.
ol:5: Concerning the seven Councils of the undivided Church, we
    affirm the teaching of the first four Councils and the Christo-
    logical clarifications of the fifth, sixth and seventh Councils, in
    so far as they are agreeable to the Holy Scriptures.
ol:6: We receive The Book of Common Prayer as set forth by
    the Church of England in 1662, together with the Ordinal
    attached to the same, as a standard for Anglican doctrine
    and discipline, and, with the Books which preceded it, as the
    standard for the Anglican tradition of worship.
ol:7: We receive the Thirty-Nine Articles of Religion of 1571,
    taken in their literal and grammatical sense, as expressing the
    Anglican response to certain doctrinal issues controverted
    at that time, and as expressing fundamental principles of
    authentic Anglican belief.
tb: In all these things, the Anglican Church in North America is
    determined by the help of God to hold and maintain, as the
    Anglican Way has received them, the doctrine, discipline and
    worship of Christ and to transmit the same, unimpaired, to
    our posterity. We seek to be and remain in full communion
    with all Anglican Churches, Dioceses and Provinces that hold
    and maintain the Historic Faith, Doctrine, Sacraments and
    Discipline of the One, Holy, Catholic, and Apostolic Church.


st:2: college of bishops resolution
st: concerning the
st:2: nicene creed
st:1: _Epiphany, 2013_
br:
l: {{/u}}resolved,{{/u}}
tb: The normative form of the Nicene Creed for the Anglican
    Church in North America is the original text as adopted by the
    Councils of Nicaea (325 A.D.) and Constantinople (381 A.D.).
    This form shall be rendered in English in the best and most accurate translation achievable.
br:
l: {{/u}}resolved,{{/u}}
tb: The Anglican Church in North America acknowledges that
    the form of the Nicene Creed customary in the West is that of
    the 1662 Book of Common Prayer, including the words “and
    the Son” (filioque), which form may be used in worship and for
    elucidation of doctrine.
br:
l: {{/u}}resolved,{{/u}}
tb: Because we are committed to the highest level of global unity
    possible, the College of Bishops of the Anglican Church in North
    America seeks advice of the Theological Commission of the Global
    Fellowship of Confessing Anglicans concerning implementation
    of the recommendation of the Lambeth Conference of 1978 to
    use the normative form of the Nicene Creed at worship.

pb:769
l: {{/u}}the{{/u}}
st:2: athanasian creed
l: Whosoever will be saved, *
l:i: before all things it is necessary that he hold the Catholic Faith.
l: Which Faith except everyone do keep whole and undefiled, *
l:i: without doubt he shall perish everlastingly.
l: And the Catholic Faith is this: *
l:i: That we worship one God in Trinity, and Trinity in Unity,
l: Neither confounding the Persons, *
l:i: nor dividing the Substance.
l: For there is one Person of the Father, another of the Son, *
l:i: and another of the Holy Ghost.
l: But the Godhead of the Father, of the Son,
l: and of the Holy Ghost, is all one, *
l:i: the Glory equal, the Majesty co-eternal.
l: Such as the Father is, such is the Son, *
l:i: and such is the Holy Ghost.
l: The Father uncreate, the Son uncreate, *
l:i: and the Holy Ghost uncreate.
l: The Father incomprehensible, the Son incomprehensible, *
l:i: and the Holy Ghost incomprehensible.
l: The Father eternal, the Son eternal, *
l:i: and the Holy Ghost eternal.
l: And yet they are not three eternals, *
l:i: but one eternal.

pb:770
l: As also there are not three incomprehensibles, nor three uncreated, *
l:i: but one uncreated, and one incomprehensible.
l: So likewise the Father is Almighty, the Son Almighty, *
l:i: and the Holy Ghost Almighty.
l: And yet they are not three Almighties, *
l:i: but one Almighty.
l: So the Father is God, the Son is God, *
l:i: and the Holy Ghost is God.
l: And yet they are not three Gods, *
l:i: but one God.
l: So likewise the Father is Lord, the Son Lord, *
l:i: and the Holy Ghost Lord.
l: And yet not three Lords, *
l:i: but one Lord.
l: For like as we are compelled by the Christian verity *
l:i: to acknowledge every Person by himself to be both God and Lord,
l: So are we forbidden by the Catholic Religion, *
l:i: to say, There be three Gods, or three Lords.
l: The Father is made of none, *
l:i: neither created, nor begotten.
l: The Son is of the Father alone, *
l:i: not made, nor created, but begotten.
l: The Holy Ghost is of the Father and of the Son, *
l:i: neither made, nor created, nor begotten, but proceeding.
l: So there is one Father, not three Fathers; one Son, not three Sons; *
l:i: one Holy Ghost, not three Holy Ghosts.
l: And in this Trinity none is afore, or after other; *
l:i: none is greater, or less than another;
l: But the whole three Persons are co-eternal together *
l:i: and co-equal.
l: So that in all things, as is aforesaid, *
l:i: the Unity in Trinity and the Trinity in Unity is to be worshipped.

pb:771
l: He therefore that will be saved *
l:i: must thus think of the Trinity.
l: Furthermore, it is necessary to everlasting salvation *
l:i: that he also believe rightly the Incarnation of our Lord Jesus Christ.
l: For the right Faith is, that we believe and confess, *
l:i: that our Lord Jesus Christ, the Son of God, is God and Man;
l: God, of the Substance of the Father, begotten before the worlds; *
l:i: and Man, of the Substance of his Mother, born in the world;
l: Perfect God and perfect Man, *
l:i: of a reasonable soul and human flesh subsisting;
l: Equal to the Father, as touching his Godhead; *
l:i: and inferior to the Father, as touching his Manhood.
l: Who, although he be God and Man, *
l:i: yet he is not two, but one Christ;
l: One, not by conversion of the Godhead into flesh, *
l:i: but by taking of the Manhood into God;
l: One altogether; not by confusion of Substance, *
l:i: but by unity of Person.
l: For as the reasonable soul and flesh is one man, *
l:i: so God and Man is one Christ;
l: Who suffered for our salvation, *
l:i: descended into hell, rose again the third day from the dead.
l: He ascended into heaven, he sitteth on the right hand of the Father, God Almighty, *
l:i: from whence he shall come to judge the quick and the dead.
l: At whose coming all men shall rise again with their bodies *
l:i: and shall give account for their own works.
l: And they that have done good shall go into life everlasting; *
l:i: and they that have done evil into everlasting fire.
br:
l: This is the Catholic Faith, *
l:i: which except a man believe faithfully, he cannot be saved.

pb:772
st: the thirty-nine
st:2: articles of religion
st:1: _of 1571_
br:
l: {{u}}i. of faith in the holy trinity{{/u}}
tb: There is but one living and true God, everlasting, without body,
    parts, or passions; of infinite power, wisdom, and goodness; the
    Maker, and Preserver of all things both visible and invisible.
    And in unity of this Godhead there be three Persons, of one
    substance, power, and eternity; the Father, the Son, and the
    Holy Ghost.
l: {{u}}ii. of the word or son of god, which was made very man{{/u}}
tb: The Son, which is the Word of the Father, begotten from
    everlasting of the Father, the very and eternal God, and of one
    substance with the Father, took Man’s nature in the womb of the
    blessed Virgin, of her substance: so that two whole and perfect
    Natures, that is to say, the Godhead and Manhood, were joined
    together in one Person, never to be divided, whereof is one Christ,
    very God, and very Man; who truly suffered, was crucified, dead,
    and buried, to reconcile his Father to us, and to be a sacrifice, not
    only for original guilt, but also for all actual sins of men.

pb:773
l: {{u}}iii. of the going down of christ into hell{{/u}}
tb: As Christ died for us, and was buried, so also is it to be believed,
    that he went down into Hell.
l: {{u}}iv. of there surrection of christ{{/u}}
tb: Christ did truly rise again from death, and took again his body,
    with flesh, bones, and all things appertaining to the perfection
    of Man’s nature; wherewith he ascended into Heaven, and there
    sitteth, until he return to judge all Men at the last day.
l: {{u}}v. of the holy ghost{{/u}}
tb: The Holy Ghost, proceeding from the Father and the Son, is of
    one substance, majesty, and glory, with the Father and the Son,
    very and eternal God.
l: {{u}}vi. of the sufficiency of the holy scriptures for salvation{{/u}}
tb: Holy Scripture containeth all things necessary to salvation: so
    that whatsoever is not read therein, nor may be proved thereby,
    is not to be required of any man, that it should be believed as
    an article of the Faith, or be thought requisite or necessary to
    salvation. In the name of the Holy Scriptures we do understand
    those Canonical Books of the Old and New Testament, of
    whose authority was never any doubt in the Church.
    Of the Names and Number of the Canonical Books
l: Genesis
l: Exodus
l: Leviticus
l: Numbers
l: Deuteronomy

pb:774
